[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring JUnit Discovery**\n\nI'm thinking about JUnit engine discovery, which is needed to include tests. I wonder if using the @ClassTemplate annotation directly with @Test methods would work. It seems @ClassTemplate needs a provider extension, and according to the JUnit docs, it requires a TestTemplateInvocationContextProvider to be registered; otherwise, it might not get called during discovery. In contrast, using ParameterizedClass looks easier. I might need to add some dependencies and consider the accessibility of my fixture for proper discovery, especially with nested classes.\n\n**Considering Classpath Scanning**\n\nI’m thinking about classpath scanning and how it might discover all class files. Is JUnit Jupiter recognizing IsTestClassWithTests? It seems like it might include static nested classes, but perhaps it doesn't have to. Maybe I should define the fixture as a static nested class inside my test file. Also, the scanner roots include entire test classes and a package filter, so it could potentially find TestClassScannerTest and its fixtures too.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0fc9b61c573a9a7a016a29109bbc048195aef30a99b2632ec8\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqKRC3zFth3WaDuH-ibryN_tfeSv-fXS3Rk2pdJXv8r9XGfA2l8IAhLtMQegNabqVXwO8VORcWbADfkYzChsU_E6jV-ag7a0YMMnF8gDNWyLUOaFoeTHVpzJT-6L-pjqCR6tH4LSlQi6jvp5GlfZ35R1qN2bCJakkjSidLVLRUnH8Jlt7zo-Lu7V06lucrZ32uQPiLohh99refP2-4Ap-120paKAivpbej-y5hvUnxnyDSaB1BAr1gt8QdFvRPdhIQLO1cRWodJftIiZiZxPYXWeOhSnW4N5sCoV9xHWbh5yT2fYwjU7Un0tKAq5bEXE2RVa_LmRv3Llfh6QVlf6RYUF2bxiPgiidZbHLBLAEGeQfDd7JLo_1tLmjHoFMVLz5-UV96cAPkGJ1dZv1-nnwK7-kCLHA2nIazLk5M5DvsPXIk8cLRDmn94QvUicdr3Z_D1z0r41SCAN2dJdhCt4t-2dML_FKhfO7UaHfVsox0asdyXIyMpaj3QkxGnFsgix2iB4RbT6-TiuGNV2i9PBN8nDkjLjx92zTQ-OMGZvyvdxFTxHMQL2Gfo5H9Wf5hx9Fb-hqqRAR9ywKWoc0xjtpfpK4J3GMH_96iwLup264p3am7GmdiCVVbLAnogbh8zUVoFvG9UyeT2oBhb